### Fundamentals

The algebra of sets is, in essence, the set-theoretic echo of the algebra of numbers. Just as arithmetic [addition](/Addition) and [multiplication](/Multiplication) possess the elegant properties of being [associative](/Associativity) and [commutative](/Commutativity), so too do set union and intersection. Similarly, the arithmetic relation "less than or equal to" is characterized by being [reflexive](/Reflexive_relation), [antisymmetric](/Antisymmetric_relation), and [transitive](/Transitive_relation)—properties mirrored by the set relation of "subset."

This field meticulously details the algebra governing the set-theoretic operations of union, intersection, and complementation, alongside the crucial relations of equality and inclusion. For those who find themselves adrift in the initial concepts, a basic introduction to [sets](/Set_(mathematics)) is available. For a more comprehensive understanding, the article on [naive set theory](/Naive_set_theory) is recommended. And for those who demand absolute rigor, a full, uncompromising [axiomatic](/Axiom) treatment can be found within [axiomatic set theory](/Axiomatic_set_theory).

